<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Coat_of_arms_of_Finland.svg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ae/Coat_of_arms_of_Finland.svg/170px-Coat_of_arms_of_Finland.svg.png" decoding="async" width="170" height="213" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ae/Coat_of_arms_of_Finland.svg/255px-Coat_of_arms_of_Finland.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ae/Coat_of_arms_of_Finland.svg/340px-Coat_of_arms_of_Finland.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="800" data-file-height="1000" /></a><figcaption>Lion as a primary <a href="/wiki/Charge_(heraldry)" title="Charge (heraldry)">charge</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Coat_of_arms_of_Finland" title="Coat of arms of Finland">coat of arms of Finland</a> (1978 design, based on the 16th-century coat of arms of the <a href="/wiki/Grand_Duke_of_Finland" title="Grand Duke of Finland">Grand Duke of Finland</a>).</figcaption></figure>
<p>The <b><a href="/wiki/Lion" title="Lion">lion</a></b> is a common <a href="/wiki/Charge_(heraldry)" title="Charge (heraldry)">charge</a> in <a href="/wiki/Heraldry" title="Heraldry">heraldry</a>. It traditionally symbolises <a href="/wiki/Courage" title="Courage">courage</a>, <a href="/wiki/Nobility" title="Nobility">nobility</a>, <a href="/wiki/Royal_family" title="Royal family">royalty</a>, strength, stateliness and <a href="/wiki/Courage" title="Courage">valour</a>, because historically the <a href="/wiki/Lion" title="Lion">lion</a> has been regarded as the "king of beasts".<sup id="cite_ref-Garai73_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Garai73-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> The lion also carries <a href="/wiki/Judeo-Christian" title="Judeo-Christian">Judeo-Christian</a> symbolism. The <a href="/wiki/Lion_of_Judah" title="Lion of Judah">Lion of Judah</a> stands in the <a href="/wiki/Emblem_of_Jerusalem" class="mw-redirect" title="Emblem of Jerusalem">coat of arms of Jerusalem</a>. Similar-looking lions can be found elsewhere, such as in the coat of arms of the Swedish royal <a href="/wiki/House_of_Bjelbo" title="House of Bjelbo">House of Bjelbo</a>, from there in turn derived into the <a href="/wiki/Coat_of_arms_of_Finland" title="Coat of arms of Finland">coat of arms of Finland</a>, formerly belonging to Sweden.
</p>
<meta property="mw:PageProp/toc" />
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="History">History</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lion_(heraldry)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: History"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Further information: <a href="/wiki/Cultural_depictions_of_lions" title="Cultural depictions of lions">Cultural depictions of lions</a></div>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Meister_des_Evangeliars_von_Echternach_001.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/Meister_des_Evangeliars_von_Echternach_001.jpg/170px-Meister_des_Evangeliars_von_Echternach_001.jpg" decoding="async" width="170" height="217" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/Meister_des_Evangeliars_von_Echternach_001.jpg/255px-Meister_des_Evangeliars_von_Echternach_001.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/Meister_des_Evangeliars_von_Echternach_001.jpg/340px-Meister_des_Evangeliars_von_Echternach_001.jpg 2x" data-file-width="942" data-file-height="1200" /></a><figcaption>A <a href="/wiki/Lion_of_Saint_Mark" title="Lion of Saint Mark">Lion of Saint Mark</a>, from the <a href="/wiki/Echternach_Gospels" title="Echternach Gospels">Echternach Gospels</a> (late 7th century).</figcaption></figure>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Geoffrey_of_Anjou_Monument.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/Geoffrey_of_Anjou_Monument.jpg/170px-Geoffrey_of_Anjou_Monument.jpg" decoding="async" width="170" height="325" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/Geoffrey_of_Anjou_Monument.jpg/255px-Geoffrey_of_Anjou_Monument.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/Geoffrey_of_Anjou_Monument.jpg/340px-Geoffrey_of_Anjou_Monument.jpg 2x" data-file-width="905" data-file-height="1729" /></a><figcaption>Enamel from the tomb of <a href="/wiki/Geoffrey_Plantagenet,_Count_of_Anjou" title="Geoffrey Plantagenet, Count of Anjou">Geoffrey Plantagenet, Count of Anjou</a> (<abbr title="circa">c.</abbr><span style="white-space:nowrap;">&#8201;1160</span>).</figcaption></figure>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Schild_konradvonth%C3%BCringen_marburg.JPG" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2e/Schild_konradvonth%C3%BCringen_marburg.JPG/170px-Schild_konradvonth%C3%BCringen_marburg.JPG" decoding="async" width="170" height="189" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2e/Schild_konradvonth%C3%BCringen_marburg.JPG/255px-Schild_konradvonth%C3%BCringen_marburg.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2e/Schild_konradvonth%C3%BCringen_marburg.JPG/340px-Schild_konradvonth%C3%BCringen_marburg.JPG 2x" data-file-width="2355" data-file-height="2625" /></a><figcaption>The shield of <a href="/wiki/Conrad_of_Thuringia" title="Conrad of Thuringia">Conrad of Thuringia</a> (<abbr title="circa">c.</abbr><span style="white-space:nowrap;">&#8201;1230s</span>), a rare example of a preserved 13th-century knightly shield, displaying the Ludovingian <i>lion barry</i>.</figcaption></figure>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Wernigeroder_Wappenbuch_034.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/63/Wernigeroder_Wappenbuch_034.jpg/170px-Wernigeroder_Wappenbuch_034.jpg" decoding="async" width="170" height="240" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/63/Wernigeroder_Wappenbuch_034.jpg/255px-Wernigeroder_Wappenbuch_034.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/63/Wernigeroder_Wappenbuch_034.jpg/340px-Wernigeroder_Wappenbuch_034.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1500" data-file-height="2115" /></a><figcaption>The coat of arms of the <a href="/wiki/Landgrave_of_Hesse" class="mw-redirect" title="Landgrave of Hesse">Landgrave of Hesse</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Wernigerode_Armorial" title="Wernigerode Armorial">Wernigerode Armorial</a> (late 15th century), shown as combining the lions of <a href="/wiki/Ludovingians" title="Ludovingians">Hesse</a>, <a href="/wiki/County_of_Katzenelnbogen" title="County of Katzenelnbogen">Katzenelnbogen</a> and <a href="/wiki/County_of_Diez" title="County of Diez">Diez</a>)</figcaption></figure>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Broderat_guldlejon,_1600-talets_slut_-_Livrustkammaren_-_100403.tif" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/da/Broderat_guldlejon%2C_1600-talets_slut_-_Livrustkammaren_-_100403.tif/lossy-page1-170px-Broderat_guldlejon%2C_1600-talets_slut_-_Livrustkammaren_-_100403.tif.jpg" decoding="async" width="170" height="286" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/da/Broderat_guldlejon%2C_1600-talets_slut_-_Livrustkammaren_-_100403.tif/lossy-page1-255px-Broderat_guldlejon%2C_1600-talets_slut_-_Livrustkammaren_-_100403.tif.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/da/Broderat_guldlejon%2C_1600-talets_slut_-_Livrustkammaren_-_100403.tif/lossy-page1-340px-Broderat_guldlejon%2C_1600-talets_slut_-_Livrustkammaren_-_100403.tif.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3146" data-file-height="5284" /></a><figcaption>Two tailed embroidered gold lion from the end of the 17th century, Sweden.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The animals of the "barbarian" (<a href="/wiki/Eurasian_nomads" title="Eurasian nomads">Eurasian</a>) predecessors of heraldic designs are likely to have been used as <a href="/wiki/Totemism" class="mw-redirect" title="Totemism">clan symbols</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">&#91;a&#93;</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Confronted_animals" title="Confronted animals">Symmetrically paired animals</a> in particular find continuation from <a href="/wiki/Migration_Period_art" title="Migration Period art">Migration Period art</a> via <a href="/wiki/Insular_art" title="Insular art">Insular art</a> to <a href="/wiki/Romanesque_art" title="Romanesque art">Romanesque art</a> and heraldry. Adopted in <a href="/wiki/Germanic_art" class="mw-redirect" title="Germanic art">Germanic tradition</a> around the <a href="/wiki/Germanic_Iron_Age" class="mw-redirect" title="Germanic Iron Age">5th century</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> they were re-interpreted in a <a href="/wiki/Germanic_Christianity" class="mw-redirect" title="Germanic Christianity">Christian context</a> in the western kingdoms of <a href="/wiki/Francia" title="Francia">Gaul</a> and <a href="/wiki/Kingdom_of_the_Lombards" title="Kingdom of the Lombards">Italy</a> in the 6th and 7th centuries. The characteristic of the lion as royal animal in particular is due to the influence of <a href="/wiki/The_Physiologus" class="mw-redirect" title="The Physiologus">the Physiologus</a>, an early Christian book about animal symbolism, originally written in Greek in the 2nd century and translated into Latin in about AD 400.
It was a predecessor of the medieval <a href="/wiki/Bestiaries" class="mw-redirect" title="Bestiaries">bestiaries</a>. At the time, few Europeans had a chance to encounter actual lions, so that painters had to rely on traditional depictions and had no actual animals as models.
</p><p>The lion as a heraldic charge is present from the very earliest development of <a href="/wiki/Heraldry" title="Heraldry">heraldry</a> in the 12th century. One of the earliest known examples of armory as it subsequently came to be practiced can be seen on the tomb of <a href="/wiki/Geoffrey_Plantagenet,_Count_of_Anjou" title="Geoffrey Plantagenet, Count of Anjou">Geoffrey Plantagenet, Count of Anjou</a>, who died in 1151.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> An enamel, probably commissioned by Geoffrey's widow between 1155 and 1160, depicts him carrying a blue shield decorated six golden lions rampant and wearing a blue helmet adorned with another lion. A chronicle dated to c. 1175 states that Geoffrey was given a shield of this description when he was knighted by his father-in-law, <a href="/wiki/Henry_I_of_England" title="Henry I of England">Henry I</a>, in 1128.<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Earlier heraldic writers attributed the <a href="/wiki/Coat_of_arms_of_England" title="Coat of arms of England">lions of England</a> to <a href="/wiki/William_the_Conqueror" title="William the Conqueror">William the Conqueror</a>, but the earliest evidence of the association of lions with the English crown is a seal bearing two lions passant, used by the future <a href="/wiki/John,_King_of_England" title="John, King of England">King John</a> during the lifetime of his father, <a href="/wiki/Henry_II_of_England" title="Henry II of England">Henry II</a>, who died in 1189.<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-CGH_173–174_9-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CGH_173–174-9">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> Since Henry was the son of Geoffrey Plantagenet, it seems reasonable to suppose that the adoption of lions as an heraldic emblem by Henry or his sons might have been inspired by Geoffrey's shield. John's elder brother, <a href="/wiki/Richard_I_of_England" title="Richard I of England">Richard the Lionheart</a>, who succeeded his father on the throne, is believed to have been the first to have borne the arms of three lions passant-guardant, still the arms of England, having earlier used two lions rampant combatant, which arms may also have belonged to his father.<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> Richard is also credited with having originated the English crest of a lion statant (now statant-guardant).<sup id="cite_ref-CGH_173–174_9-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CGH_173–174-9">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Apart from the lions of the <a href="/wiki/List_of_coats_of_arms_of_the_House_of_Plantagenet" class="mw-redirect" title="List of coats of arms of the House of Plantagenet">Plantagenet</a> (England and Normandy) coat of arms, 12th-century examples of lions used as heraldic charges include the <a href="/wiki/Hohenstaufen" title="Hohenstaufen">Staufen (Hohenstaufen)</a> and <a href="/wiki/House_of_Wittelsbach" title="House of Wittelsbach">Wittelsbach</a> (<a href="/wiki/Electoral_Palatinate" title="Electoral Palatinate">Palatinate</a>) coats of arms, both deriving from <a href="/wiki/Henry_the_Lion" title="Henry the Lion">Henry the Lion</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Royal_coat_of_arms_of_Scotland" class="mw-redirect" title="Royal coat of arms of Scotland">royal coat of arms of Scotland</a>, attributed to <a href="/wiki/William_the_Lion" title="William the Lion">William the Lion</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">&#91;b&#93;</a></sup>
the <a href="/wiki/Coat_of_arms_of_Denmark" title="Coat of arms of Denmark">coat of arms of Denmark</a>, first used by <a href="/wiki/Canute_VI_of_Denmark" title="Canute VI of Denmark">Canute VI</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Coat_of_arms_of_Flanders" title="Coat of arms of Flanders">coat of arms of Flanders</a> (<a href="/wiki/Duchy_of_J%C3%BClich" title="Duchy of Jülich">Jülich</a>), first used by <a href="/wiki/Philip_I,_Count_of_Flanders" title="Philip I, Count of Flanders">Philip I</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Coat_of_arms_of_Le%C3%B3n" class="mw-redirect" title="Coat of arms of León">coat of arms of León</a>, an example of <a href="/wiki/Canting_arms" title="Canting arms">canting arms</a><sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14">&#91;c&#93;</a></sup> attributed to <a href="/wiki/Alfonso_VII_of_Le%C3%B3n_and_Castile" title="Alfonso VII of León and Castile">Alfonso VII</a> (1126), and the <a href="/wiki/Coat_of_arms_of_Bohemia" class="mw-redirect" title="Coat of arms of Bohemia">coat of arms of Bohemia</a>, first granted to <a href="/wiki/Vladislaus_II,_Duke_of_Bohemia" class="mw-redirect" title="Vladislaus II, Duke of Bohemia">Vladislaus II</a>.
</p><p>Coats of arms of the 13th century include those of the <a href="/wiki/House_of_Sverre" title="House of Sverre">House of Sverre</a> (<a href="/wiki/Coat_of_arms_of_Norway" title="Coat of arms of Norway">coat of arms of Norway</a>), the <a href="/wiki/Ludovingians" title="Ludovingians">Ludovingians</a> (the <a href="/wiki/Coat_of_arms_of_Hesse" title="Coat of arms of Hesse">lion of Hesse</a> used by <a href="/wiki/Conrad_of_Thuringia" title="Conrad of Thuringia">Conrad of Thuringia</a>), <a href="/wiki/Henry_V_of_Luxembourg" class="mw-redirect" title="Henry V of Luxembourg">Luxembourg</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Kingdom_of_Ruthenia" class="mw-redirect" title="Kingdom of Ruthenia">kingdom of Ruthenia</a> (<a href="/wiki/Coat_of_arms_of_Lviv" title="Coat of arms of Lviv">Volhynia</a>), the <a href="/wiki/House_of_Habsburg" title="House of Habsburg">House of Habsburg</a> (the Habsburgs all but abandoned their original coat of arms after gaining the <a href="/wiki/Duchy_of_Austria" title="Duchy of Austria">Duchy of Austria</a> in the 1270s, but it remained in use in derived lineages such as the <a href="/wiki/House_of_Kyburg" class="mw-redirect" title="House of Kyburg">House of Kyburg</a>), the <a href="/wiki/Coat_of_arms_of_Bulgaria" title="Coat of arms of Bulgaria">kingdom of Bulgaria</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Armenian_Kingdom_of_Cilicia" title="Armenian Kingdom of Cilicia">Armenian Kingdom of Cilicia</a> (<a href="/wiki/Rubenids" title="Rubenids">Rubenids</a>).
</p><p>Unlike the <a href="/wiki/Eagle_(heraldry)" title="Eagle (heraldry)">eagle</a>, which is comparatively rare in heraldry because it was reserved as an <a href="/wiki/Reichsadler" title="Reichsadler">imperial symbol</a>, the lion became a symbol of <a href="/wiki/Chivalry" title="Chivalry">chivalry</a> and was not restricted to royal coats of arms. The <a href="/wiki/Z%C3%BCrich_armorial" title="Zürich armorial">Zürich armorial</a> (14th century) has a number of coats of arms with lions, most of them of <a href="/wiki/Ministeriales" class="mw-redirect" title="Ministeriales">ministeriales</a> of the House of Habsburg.
</p><p>The lion in the <a href="/wiki/Coat_of_arms_of_Bohemia" class="mw-redirect" title="Coat of arms of Bohemia">coat of arms of Bohemia</a> is depicted with two tails (<i>à la queue fourchée</i>). According to <a href="/wiki/Claude-Fran%C3%A7ois_M%C3%A9nestrier" title="Claude-François Ménestrier">Ménestrier</a>, this is due to a jest made by <a href="/wiki/Frederick_I,_Holy_Roman_Emperor" class="mw-redirect" title="Frederick I, Holy Roman Emperor">Emperor Frederick</a>, who granted <a href="/wiki/Vladislaus_II,_Duke_of_Bohemia" class="mw-redirect" title="Vladislaus II, Duke of Bohemia">Vladislaus II, Duke of Bohemia</a> a coat of arms with a lion <i>coué</i>, that is, with its tail between its legs. Vladislaus' men refused to follow this emblem, calling it an ape, so that Frederick agreed to <a href="/wiki/Augmentation_of_honour" title="Augmentation of honour">improve</a> the arms by giving the lion not just one but two erect tails.<sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Attitudes">Attitudes</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lion_(heraldry)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Attitudes"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>As many <i><a href="/wiki/Attitude_(heraldry)" title="Attitude (heraldry)">attitudes</a></i> (positions) now exist in heraldry as the heraldist's imagination can conjure, as a result of the ever-increasing need for differentiation, but very few of these were apparently known to medieval heralds.<sup id="cite_ref-Fox-Davies172_16-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fox-Davies172-16">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> One distinction commonly made (especially among French heralds), although it may be of limited importance, is the distinction of lions in the walking positions as <i><a href="/wiki/Leopard_(heraldry)" title="Leopard (heraldry)">leopards</a></i>.<sup id="cite_ref-Fox-Davies172_16-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fox-Davies172-16">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> The following table summarizes the principal attitudes of heraldic lions:
</p>
<table class="wikitable">

<tbody><tr>
<th>Attitude
</th>
<th>Example
</th>
<th>Description
</th></tr>
<tr>
<td><i>Rampant</i>
</td>
<td><figure class="mw-halign-center" typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Lion_Rampant.svg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/75/Lion_Rampant.svg/100px-Lion_Rampant.svg.png" decoding="async" width="100" height="105" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/75/Lion_Rampant.svg/150px-Lion_Rampant.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/75/Lion_Rampant.svg/200px-Lion_Rampant.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="400" data-file-height="420" /></a><figcaption></figcaption></figure>
</td>
<td>A "lion rampant" is depicted in profile standing erect with forepaws raised.<sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup> The position of the hind legs varies according to local custom: the lion may stand on both hind legs, braced wide apart, or on only one, with the other also raised to strike; the word <i>rampant</i> is often omitted, especially in early blazon, as this is the most usual position of a carnivorous quadruped;
<p><i>Note:</i> the term <i>segreant</i> denotes the same position, but is only used in reference to winged four-legged beasts like <a href="/wiki/Griffin" title="Griffin">griffins</a> and <a href="/wiki/European_dragon" title="European dragon">dragons</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td><i>Passant</i>
</td>
<td><figure class="mw-halign-center" typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Lion_Passant.svg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f3/Lion_Passant.svg/100px-Lion_Passant.svg.png" decoding="async" width="100" height="83" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f3/Lion_Passant.svg/150px-Lion_Passant.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f3/Lion_Passant.svg/200px-Lion_Passant.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="420" data-file-height="350" /></a><figcaption></figcaption></figure>
</td>
<td>A "lion passant" is walking, with the right fore paw raised and all others on the ground.<sup id="cite_ref-Fox-Davies181_19-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fox-Davies181-19">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup> A "Lion of England" denotes a <i>lion passant guardant Or</i>, used as an <a href="/wiki/Augmentation_of_honour" title="Augmentation of honour">augmentation</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Fox-Davies181_19-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fox-Davies181-19">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup>
<p><i>Note:</i> A lion thus depicted may be called a "leopard" (see discussion below).
</p>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td><i>Statant</i>
</td>
<td><figure class="mw-halign-center" typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Lion_Statant.svg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/34/Lion_Statant.svg/100px-Lion_Statant.svg.png" decoding="async" width="100" height="83" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/34/Lion_Statant.svg/150px-Lion_Statant.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/34/Lion_Statant.svg/200px-Lion_Statant.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="420" data-file-height="350" /></a><figcaption></figcaption></figure>
</td>
<td>A "lion statant" is standing, all four feet on the ground, usually with the forepaws together.<sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-20">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup> This posture is more frequent in <a href="/wiki/Crest_(heraldry)" title="Crest (heraldry)">crests</a> than in charges on shields.<sup id="cite_ref-Fox-Davies183_21-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fox-Davies183-21">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td><i>Salient</i>
</td>
<td><figure class="mw-halign-center" typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Lion_Salient.svg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5d/Lion_Salient.svg/100px-Lion_Salient.svg.png" decoding="async" width="100" height="111" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5d/Lion_Salient.svg/150px-Lion_Salient.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5d/Lion_Salient.svg/200px-Lion_Salient.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="380" data-file-height="420" /></a><figcaption></figcaption></figure>
</td>
<td>A "lion salient" is leaping, with both hind legs together on the ground and both forelegs together in the air.<sup id="cite_ref-Fox-Davies183_21-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fox-Davies183-21">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup> This is a very rare position for a lion,<sup id="cite_ref-Fox-Davies183_21-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fox-Davies183-21">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup> but is also used of other heraldic beasts.
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td><i>Sejant</i>
</td>
<td><figure class="mw-halign-center" typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Lion_Sejant.svg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d2/Lion_Sejant.svg/100px-Lion_Sejant.svg.png" decoding="async" width="100" height="111" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d2/Lion_Sejant.svg/150px-Lion_Sejant.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d2/Lion_Sejant.svg/200px-Lion_Sejant.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="380" data-file-height="420" /></a><figcaption></figcaption></figure>
</td>
<td>A "lion sejant" is sitting on his haunches, with both forepaws on the ground.<sup id="cite_ref-Fox-Davies184_22-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fox-Davies184-22">&#91;19&#93;</a></sup>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td><i>Sejant erect</i>
</td>
<td><figure class="mw-halign-center" typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Lion_Sejant_Erect.svg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/Lion_Sejant_Erect.svg/100px-Lion_Sejant_Erect.svg.png" decoding="async" width="100" height="97" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/Lion_Sejant_Erect.svg/150px-Lion_Sejant_Erect.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/Lion_Sejant_Erect.svg/200px-Lion_Sejant_Erect.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="390" data-file-height="380" /></a><figcaption></figcaption></figure>
</td>
<td>A "lion sejant erect" is seated on its haunches, but with its body erect and both forepaws raised in the "rampant" position (this is sometimes termed "sejant-rampant").<sup id="cite_ref-Fox-Davies184_22-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fox-Davies184-22">&#91;19&#93;</a></sup>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td><i>Couchant</i>
</td>
<td><figure class="mw-halign-center" typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Lion_Couchant.svg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/74/Lion_Couchant.svg/125px-Lion_Couchant.svg.png" decoding="async" width="125" height="74" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/74/Lion_Couchant.svg/188px-Lion_Couchant.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/74/Lion_Couchant.svg/250px-Lion_Couchant.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="490" data-file-height="290" /></a><figcaption></figcaption></figure>
</td>
<td>A "lion couchant" is lying down, but with the head raised.<sup id="cite_ref-Fox-Davies185_23-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fox-Davies185-23">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup>
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td><i>Dormant</i>
</td>
<td><figure class="mw-halign-center" typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Lion_Dormant.svg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/Lion_Dormant.svg/125px-Lion_Dormant.svg.png" decoding="async" width="125" height="70" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/Lion_Dormant.svg/188px-Lion_Dormant.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/Lion_Dormant.svg/250px-Lion_Dormant.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="480" data-file-height="270" /></a><figcaption></figcaption></figure>
</td>
<td>A "lion dormant" is lying down with its eyes closed and head lowered, resting upon the forepaws, as if asleep.<sup id="cite_ref-Fox-Davies185_23-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Fox-Davies185-23">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>Other terms are used to describe the lion's position in further detail. Each coat of arms has a right and left (i.e. <i>dexter</i> and <i>sinister</i>) side - <i>with respect to the person carrying the shield</i> - so the left side of the shield as drawn on the page (thus the right side to the shield bearer) is called the dexter side. The lion's head is normally seen in agreement with the overall position, facing dexter (left) unless otherwise stated. If a lion's <i>whole body</i> is turned to face right, he is <i>to sinister</i> or <i>contourné</i>. If his <i>whole body</i> faces the viewer, he is <i>affronté</i>. If his <i>head only</i> faces the viewer he is <i>guardant</i> or <i>gardant</i>, and if he looks back over his shoulder he is <i>regardant</i>. These adjectives follow any other adjectives of position.
</p><p>A lion (or other beast) <i>coward</i> carries the tail between its hind legs.<sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24">&#91;21&#93;</a></sup> The tail also may be knotted (<i>nowed</i>), forked (<i>queue fourchée</i>), doubled (<i>double-queued</i>; as in the arms of the kingdom of Bohemia), or cut off (<i>defamed</i>).
</p>
<div class="center">
