<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Notes">Notes</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Lion_(heraldry)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Notes"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="reflist reflist-lower-alpha">
<div class="mw-references-wrap"><ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-3"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-3">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">"&#91;Animal style designs&#93; have also been explained as totems venerated by the various clans of nomads as ancestors. Their transformation into clan symbols would have followed naturally and easily. The heraldic beasts of medieval chivalry, which include many deer and felines like those on the British royal coat of arms, may certainly be traces back to emblematic devices of later barbarian tribes from central Asia."<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-13"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-13">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Hopingius, <i>De Insigniis</i> (1642) claimed that the use of the red lion as an emblem goes back to the <a href="/wiki/Picts" title="Picts">Picts</a><sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-14"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-14">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The actual etymology of <i><a href="/wiki/Kingdom_of_Le%C3%B3n" title="Kingdom of León">León</a> is </i><span title="Ancient Greek (to 1453)-language text"><span lang="grc"><a href="/wiki/Roman_legion" title="Roman legion">Legion (Λεγίων)</a></span></span><i>.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (September 2019)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup></i></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-39"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-39">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Accorded to the city, gifted by Charles V in 1554. The year number is encoded in the biblical motto, <span title="Latin-language text"><i lang="la">Absorta est mors in victoria</i></span>, from Corinthians 15:54 <sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38">&#91;35&#93;</a></sup></span>
</li>
</ol></div></div>
